06387nam a22011535i 9780691187907DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911879077 a10.1515/97806911879072doi  a(DE-B1597)502976  a(OCoLC)1080938485  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aBIO0220002bisacsh04a792.802/80922231 aLeontis, Artemis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEva Palmer Sikelianos :bA Life in Ruins /cArtemis Leontis. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b57 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChronology -- tCHAPTER 1. Sapphic Performances -- tCHAPTER 2. Weaving -- tCHAPTER 3. Patron of Byzantine Music -- tCHAPTER 4. Drama -- tCHAPTER 5. Writing -- tEPILOGUE. Recollecting a Life -- tAppendix: Cast of Characters -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first biography of a visionary twentieth-century American performer who devoted her life to the revival of ancient Greek cultureThis is the first biography to tell the fascinating story of Eva Palmer Sikelianos (1874-1952), an American actor, director, composer, and weaver best known for reviving the Delphic Festivals. Yet, as Artemis Leontis reveals, Palmer's most spectacular performance was her daily revival of ancient Greek life. For almost half a century, dressed in handmade Greek tunics and sandals, she sought to make modern life freer and more beautiful through a creative engagement with the ancients. Along the way, she crossed paths with other seminal modern artists such as Natalie Clifford Barney, Renée Vivien, Isadora Duncan, Susan Glaspell, George Cram Cook, Richard Strauss, Dimitri Mitropoulos, Nikos Kazantzakis, George Seferis, Henry Miller, Paul Robeson, and Ted Shawn.Brilliant and gorgeous, with floor-length auburn hair, Palmer was a wealthy New York debutante who studied Greek at Bryn Mawr College before turning her back on conventional society to live a lesbian life in Paris. She later followed Raymond Duncan (brother of Isadora) and his wife to Greece and married the Greek poet Angelos Sikelianos in 1907. With single-minded purpose, Palmer re-created ancient art forms, staging Greek tragedy with her own choreography, costumes, and even music. Having exhausted her inheritance, she returned to the United States in 1933, was blacklisted for criticizing American imperialism during the Cold War, and was barred from returning to Greece until just before her death.Drawing on hundreds of newly discovered letters and featuring many previously unpublished photographs, this biography vividly re-creates the unforgettable story of a remarkable nonconformist whom one contemporary described as "the only ancient Greek I ever knew."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDancezGreecexHistoryy20th century. 0aDancerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh  aAngelos Sikelianos.  aByzantine music.  aDelphic Festivals.  aEva Palmer Sikelianos.  aEvion Panharmonium.  aGreece.  aGreek chorus.  aGreek culture.  aGreek drama.  aGreek poetry.  aGreek prototype.  aGreek society.  aGreek tragedy.  aHellenism.  aKhorshed Naoroji.  aKonstantinos Psachos.  aPaler Sikelianos.  aParis.  aPenelope Sikelianos.  aRaymond Duncan.  aSappho.  aTed Shawn.  aUpward Panic.  aancient Greek life.  aancient Greek models.  aconventional society.  acultural biography.  adaily life.  alesbian.  anonconformist.  aphotographs.  apolitical action.  aweaving.  awri